Next, the area of the triangle bounded by the $x$-axis, $y$-axis, and $y = 2x - 6$ has vertices at $(0,0)$, $(3,0)$, and $(0,-6)$. Its area is $\frac{1}{2} \times 3 \times 6 = 9$.

The second triangle is bounded by the $x$-axis, $y = 2x - 6$, and $x = d$. For $d > 3$, its vertices are $(3,0)$, $(d,0)$, and $(d, 2d - 6)$. The area is $\frac{1}{2} \times (d - 3) \times (2d - 6) = (d - 3)^2$. Setting $9 = \frac{1}{4}(d - 3)^2$ gives $(d - 3)^2 = 36$, so $d - 3 = 6$ (since $d > e = 0$), yielding $d = 9$.",
